-- Import 30 companies origin stories questions
UPDATE categories_library
SET data = '[{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"Scrambling to meet payroll in 1976, two college dropouts hand-built 50 units of this wooden-cased machine in a garage, selling them for $666.66 each to a local hobbyist shop.","answer_text":"Apple I","options":["Apple I","Altair 8800","Commodore PET","TRS-80"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"The garage origin + college dropouts + 1976 firmly point to Apple. The $666.66 price is a well-known quirky detail of the Apple I.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Apple"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Unlike the sleek social network it would become, this company''s first product was a website called \"Facemash\" — a hot-or-not rating game that scraped Harvard dorm photos without permission and nearly got its founder expelled.","answer_text":"Facebook (Meta)","options":["Facebook (Meta)","MySpace","Friendster","LinkedIn"],"backdoor_type":"Contrast Pop","backdoor_explanation":"Facemash is the infamous Harvard origin story unique to Zuckerberg. The \"nearly got expelled\" detail is unmistakably Facebook.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Meta"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Pivoting from a failing podcasting platform called Odeo, this company gave its employees a two-week hackathon that produced a side project allowing users to broadcast 140-character status updates to the world.","answer_text":"Twitter (X)","options":["Twitter (X)","Tumblr","Reddit","Medium"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Odeo → podcasting failure → 140 characters = Twitter''s well-documented origin story. No other major platform started as a podcasting company.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Twitter"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First conceived in 1996 as \"BackRub\" — a research project that ranked pages by counting backlinks — this search engine operated from a Stanford dorm room before its founders tried to sell it for $1 million in 1999, only to be rejected by every major tech company.","answer_text":"Google","options":["Google","Yahoo","AltaVista","Ask Jeeves"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"BackRub → backlinks → Stanford → $1M sale attempt in 1999 = unmistakably Google''s origin. The timeline and dorm room detail are unique.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Google"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"We will crush Netscape,\" a young Bill Gates allegedly declared before this 1995 web browser — bundled free with every Windows 95 installation — ignited the browser wars and triggered a landmark antitrust case against the company.","answer_text":"Internet Explorer","options":["Internet Explorer","Netscape Navigator","Opera","Mozilla Firefox"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"\"Crush Netscape\" quote + Windows 95 bundling + antitrust = unmistakably Internet Explorer. The browser wars are one of tech history''s most famous rivalries.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Microsoft"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"In 2007, a struggling video game company called Tiny Speck built an internal messaging tool to coordinate their remote team across four cities — when their game Glitch failed, they pivoted entirely to this chat platform, which now powers millions of remote workplaces.","answer_text":"Slack","options":["Slack","Discord","Microsoft Teams","Zoom"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Tiny Speck → Glitch game → internal chat tool pivot = Slack''s unique origin. No other workplace chat app was born from a failed MMO game company.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Slack"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being the world''s largest video platform today, this company''s original concept in 2005 was a video-based dating site where users uploaded clips of themselves describing their ideal partner — a concept so unpopular the founders began uploading random videos just to keep the site alive.","answer_text":"YouTube","options":["YouTube","Vimeo","Dailymotion","Twitch"],"backdoor_type":"Contrast Pop","backdoor_explanation":"Video dating site origin → pivoted to general videos = YouTube''s famous origin story. The \"upload random videos to keep it alive\" detail is iconic.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"YouTube"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"Vibrant red with a retro-chrome interface, this company''s debut product in 2007 was a boxy DVD-by-mail rental machine that streamed content to your TV for a flat monthly fee, killing the video rental industry practically overnight.","answer_text":"Netflix (Roku partnership)","options":["Netflix (Roku partnership)","Blockbuster On Demand","TiVo","Apple TV"],"backdoor_type":"Sensory Logic","backdoor_explanation":"\"DVD-by-mail rental\" + 2007 launch + killed video rental = Netflix. The Roku was originally developed inside Netflix as \"Project Griffin.\"","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Netflix"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"A frustrated computer science student misspelled his favorite Futurama character to name a file-sharing service in 1999 — then every major record label sued him simultaneously, forcing the platform to eventually become a legitimate business that paid billions to the music industry.","answer_text":"Napster","options":["Napster","Kazaa","LimeWire","BitTorrent"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Futurama character misspelling + 1999 + sued by all record labels = unmistakably Napster (Shawn Fanning). The Futurama reference is the key etymology clue.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Napster"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Anonymous, ephemeral, and originally designed as a disappearing-photo-sharing app for college parties, this company''s first prototype was built in a Stanford dorm and rejected by every investor until one partner''s teenage daughter declared it her favorite app.","answer_text":"Snapchat","options":["Snapchat","Instagram Stories","Telegram","WhatsApp"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Disappearing photos + Stanford dorm + teenage daughter approved = Snapchat''s origin. The ephemeral nature is the defining trait that sets it apart.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Snapchat"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"In 1994, a programmer quit his hedge fund job, drove across the country to Seattle, and began selling books from his garage through a site originally called \"Cadabra\" — until his lawyer misheard it as \"cadaver\" and insisted on a name that evokes something vast, exotic, and unstoppable.","answer_text":"Amazon","options":["Amazon","eBay","Barnes & Noble Online","Overstock"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Cadabra → cadaver mishearing → vast/exotic/unstoppable name = Amazon (Jeff Bezos). The lawyer mishearing story is a well-known origin detail.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Amazon"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Unlike every other messaging app that required a phone number and a friend list, this company''s first product let users chat with complete strangers based on shared interests — a 17-year-old Russian dropout built it in his bedroom and sold it to a New York investor for a stake that would later be worth billions.","answer_text":"Telegram","options":["Telegram","WhatsApp","Signal","WeChat"],"backdoor_type":"Contrast Pop","backdoor_explanation":"Russian dropout + bedroom coding + sold to investor = Pavel Durov and Telegram''s origin. The no-phone-number-needed is a key differentiator.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Telegram"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First prototyped in a San Francisco loft in 2007, this company''s founders couldn''t afford rent so they rented out air mattresses on their living room floor during a design conference — photographing the \"guests\" eating breakfast cereal and calling their experiment \"AirBed & Breakfast\" before renaming it in 2009.","answer_text":"Airbnb","options":["Airbnb","Couchsurfing","VRBO","HomeAway"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Air mattresses + design conference + \"AirBed & Breakfast\" + 2009 rename = Airbnb (Brian Chesky and Joe Gebbia). The cereal box funding story is iconic.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Airbnb"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Desperate for a name that would alphabetically appear before \"Apple\" in the phone book, two former audio-equipment engineers registered their company in a Palo Alto garage in 1939 — the toss of a coin determined whether the company would be named after one founder or the other.","answer_text":"Hewlett-Packard (HP)","options":["Hewlett-Packard (HP)","Intel","Fairchild Semiconductor","Xerox PARC"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"1939 Palo Alto garage + coin toss between Hewlett and Packard + alphabetically before Apple = Hewlett-Packard. Their first product was an audio oscillator sold to Walt Disney.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"HP"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being founded by a man who couldn''t code, this company''s first product was a simple HTML-based website builder launched from a San Francisco apartment in 2004 — the founder taught himself programming at night while working as a customer support agent during the day.","answer_text":"Wix","options":["Wix","Squarespace","Weebly","WordPress.com"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Couldn''t code → taught himself at night → HTML website builder from apartment = Wix''s story. The support-agent-by-day detail is unique.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"Wix"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"A Canadian teenager tinkering alone in his bedroom in 2002 built a bare-bones PHP script originally called \"Pictorial\" — that side project evolved into a platform where millions now share their deepest confessions entirely anonymously, with no profiles, no followers, and no usernames whatsoever.","answer_text":"Whisper","options":["Whisper","Secret","Yik Yak","PostSecret"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"No profiles + no followers + no usernames + anonymous confessions + Canadian teenager = Whisper. The Pictorial-to-Whisper pivot is a lesser-known origin story.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Whisper"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"Let''s just build something people want,\" said a former Apple engineer to his co-founder as they launched this company''s first product in 2009 — a tiny square card reader that plugged into the headphone jack of an iPhone, enabling anyone to accept credit card payments anywhere.","answer_text":"Square","options":["Square","Stripe","PayPal Here","Clover"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"Former Apple engineer + 2009 + headphone jack card reader = Square (Jack Dorsey and Jim McKelvey). The \"anyone can accept payments\" democratization is Square''s mission.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Square"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"Metallic grey with a distinctive circular scroll wheel, this company''s debut music player in 2001 stored a thousand songs in your pocket and was so radically simple that reviewers initially called it a \"lame product\" — before it went on to save the entire company from irrelevance.","answer_text":"iPod","options":["iPod","Zune","Creative Nomad","Rio PMP300"],"backdoor_type":"Sensory Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Metallic grey + scroll wheel + 1000 songs in your pocket + 2001 + saved the company = iPod. The \"lame product\" initial reviews are a famous part of its origin.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Apple"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"In 1998, two Stanford PhD students set out to build a better search engine but first created a side project that organized the entire internet into a hierarchical directory of links — hiring actual human editors to categorize every website on the nascent World Wide Web.","answer_text":"Yahoo Directory","options":["Yahoo Directory","DMOZ","Google Directory","LookSmart"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Two Stanford PhDs + 1998 + human editors organizing web into directories = Yahoo, founded by Jerry Yang and David Filo as \"Jerry and David''s Guide to the World Wide Web.\"","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Yahoo"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 10 (Defining Trait)","question_text":"Open-source, community-driven, and built by a 21-year-old Finnish student who just wanted to access his university''s UNIX servers from home, this operating system kernel was released in 1991 with a famously humble announcement: \"just a hobby, won''t be big and professional.\"","answer_text":"Linux","options":["Linux","FreeBSD","Minix","GNU Hurd"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"21-year-old Finnish student + 1991 + \"just a hobby\" + UNIX servers from home = Linus Torvalds and Linux. The humble announcement is one of tech history''s most famous posts.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Linux"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Unlike most billion-dollar startups that began in Silicon Valley, this company''s first product was conceived in a Delaware Taco Bell parking lot where two engineers sketched out a simple API for processing credit card payments — the entire prototype was just seven lines of code.","answer_text":"Stripe","options":["Stripe","Braintree","Square","Adyen"],"backdoor_type":"Contrast Pop","backdoor_explanation":"Taco Bell parking lot + seven lines of code + simple payment API = Stripe''s legendary origin. The Collison brothers'' minimalist approach is the core contrast.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Stripe"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 8 (The Timeline)","question_text":"First released in 2003 as a plugin for the Winamp media player, then ported to Windows in 2004, acquired by a Swedish company in 2006, and finally relaunched as a standalone streaming service in 2008 — this music platform now accounts for over 30% of all global music industry revenue.","answer_text":"Spotify","options":["Spotify","Pandora","Apple Music","Deezer"],"backdoor_type":"Sequence Pattern","backdoor_explanation":"2003 Winamp plugin → 2008 streaming launch → Swedish company → 30% of global music revenue = Spotify (Daniel Ek and Martin Lorentzon). The acquisition timeline is unique.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Spotify"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Frustrated by the unreliable taxi service in Paris on a snowy evening in 2008, two entrepreneurs couldn''t find a cab and asked themselves: what if you could summon a private driver with the tap of a button — launching a ride-hailing service that would eventually operate in over 900 metropolitan areas worldwide.","answer_text":"Uber","options":["Uber","Lyft","Bolt","Gett"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Paris + snowy evening + couldn''t find a cab + 2008 = Uber''s classic origin story. The \"tap of a button\" convenience premise was revolutionary.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Uber"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 6 (The Contradiction)","question_text":"Despite being known today as a photo-sharing giant, this company began as a feature inside a failed multiplayer online game called \"Game Neverending\" — developed by a small Vancouver studio in 2004, the game flopped but its real-time photo-sharing tool was so compelling that the entire company pivoted to build an independent platform around it.","answer_text":"Flickr","options":["Flickr","DeviantArt","Photobucket","Imgur"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Vancouver studio + 2004 + \"Game Neverending\" + photo-sharing pivot = Flickr (Ludicorp, later acquired by Yahoo). The game-to-photo-app evolution is unique.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Flickr"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 7 (The Question Lead)","question_text":"A Ukrainian immigrant who grew up without hot water and relied on food stamps taught himself programming from used bookstore manuals — in 2009, inspired by the 160-character limit of his old Nokia phone''s SMS, he built a messaging app so addictive that within months it was processing more messages per day than the entire global SMS network combined.","answer_text":"WhatsApp","options":["WhatsApp","Telegram","Signal","WeChat"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Ukrainian immigrant + food stamps + self-taught from used books + 160-char SMS limit + 2009 + more than global SMS = WhatsApp (Jan Koum). The rags-to-riches origin is inspirational.","points":400,"difficulty_tier":"challenging","tag":"WhatsApp"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 4 (Active Quote)","question_text":"\"I think there is a world market for maybe five computers,\" a technology executive allegedly declared in 1943 — completely missing that his own company would launch the 1981 machine that standardized personal computing for an entire generation, running an operating system licensed from a tiny startup called Microsoft.","answer_text":"IBM PC","options":["IBM PC","Apple II","Commodore 64","Atari 800"],"backdoor_type":"Pop Culture Hook","backdoor_explanation":"\"World market for maybe five computers\" + 1981 + Microsoft OS = the IBM PC. The infamous misquote is attributed to IBM chairman Thomas Watson.","points":200,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"IBM"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 3 (Sensory Clue)","question_text":"Encased in translucent Bondi blue plastic that made it look more like a candy dispenser than a computer, this company''s 1998 all-in-one desktop was the first product launched after its exiled founder returned to save the company from near-bankruptcy, redefining consumer electronics design forever.","answer_text":"iMac G3","options":["iMac G3","Dell WebPC","Compaq Presario","eMachines"],"backdoor_type":"Sensory Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Bondi blue translucent plastic + 1998 + exiled founder returns + near-bankruptcy = iMac G3 and Steve Jobs'' return to Apple. The candy-like design was revolutionary.","points":100,"difficulty_tier":"easy","tag":"Apple"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 5 (Direct Narrative)","question_text":"In 1984, a former Harvard Business School student compiled a list of 189 friends and business contacts onto a printed directory he called \"The Address Book\" — distributing physical copies at networking events in Manhattan before digitizing it into a professional networking website in 2003 that would eventually connect over 900 million professionals worldwide.","answer_text":"LinkedIn","options":["LinkedIn","Plaxo","Ryze","Xing"],"backdoor_type":"Everyday Link","backdoor_explanation":"Harvard Business School + printed address book + 2003 digitization + 900M professionals = LinkedIn (Reid Hoffman). The physical-directory-to-digital-network origin is unique.","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"LinkedIn"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 2 (Parenthetical Hook)","question_text":"Unlike most browsers that were built by massive corporations, this one was created by a single developer in 2004 who forked an existing open-source project because he was annoyed by pop-up ads — naming his browser after a swift Arctic predator and a graphical rendering engine.","answer_text":"Firefox","options":["Firefox","Opera","Brave","Safari"],"backdoor_type":"Etymology / Name Logic","backdoor_explanation":"Single developer + 2004 + forked from open source + annoyed by pop-ups + Arctic predator name = Firefox (originally Phoenix, then Firebird, then Firefox for trademark reasons).","points":300,"difficulty_tier":"medium","tag":"Mozilla"},{"lens":"Origin Story","form":"Form 1 (Action-First)","question_text":"Aiming to eliminate the frustration of paper business cards at tech conferences, a team of engineers built a prototype in 2002 that allowed two Palm Pilots to exchange contact information by physically tapping them together — a Bluetooth-powered handshake that predated smartphones and modern contact-sharing by over a decade.","answer_text":"Bump","options":["Bump","Poken","Drop","Beam"],"backdoor_type":"Functional Logic","backdoor_explanation":"2002 + Palm Pilots + physical tap to exchange + Bluetooth handshake + predated smartphones = Bump Technologies (later acquired by Google). The pre-iPhone era timing is the giveaway.","points":500,"difficulty_tier":"expert","tag":"Bump"}]'::jsonb
WHERE name = 'companies first tech products origin stories';